    mechanism:
      "Endogenous adrenal steroid hormone produced primarily by the zona reticularis of the adrenal cortex, with smaller amounts from gonads and brain. The most abundant circulating steroid in humans (mostly as the sulfated form DHEA-S, which serves as a stable reservoir). DHEA serves as a **precursor hormone** that converts downstream to androstenedione → testosterone → estradiol via aromatization (in both sexes), and to androstenediol and other intermediates. **Mechanism — biological functions**: (1) **Sex steroid precursor**: in women, DHEA contributes to ~50–75% of circulating androgens and a substantial fraction of estrogens (especially post-menopause when ovarian production declines); in men, DHEA's contribution is smaller relative to gonadal testosterone but still significant. (2) **Direct receptor activity**: DHEA itself binds GABA-A receptors (modulatory effects on mood and anxiety), NMDA receptors (cognitive effects), sigma-1 receptors (neuroprotection), and PPAR-α (metabolic effects). (3) **Cortisol antagonism**: DHEA opposes some glucocorticoid effects at the cellular level — the DHEA:cortisol ratio is sometimes used as a marker of stress resilience. (4) **Immune modulation**: DHEA enhances some Th1 immune responses and reduces inflammatory cytokine production at physiological levels. (5) **Vascular effects**: improved endothelial function in some studies. **Age-related decline**: DHEA peaks around age 25 and declines ~10% per decade thereafter — by age 75, levels are typically 10–20% of young-adult peak. The 'adrenopause' decline is more pronounced and earlier than gonadal hormonal decline. This decline drove substantial interest in DHEA as a longevity-supplement starting in the 1990s. **Regulatory status — uniquely OTC**: DHEA is the only steroid hormone available over-the-counter in the United States, due to a regulatory carve-out in DSHEA (1994 Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act). All other steroid hormones (testosterone, estradiol, progesterone, cortisol) require prescription. The OTC status makes DHEA accessible but also produces variable product quality — third-party testing matters. DHEA is banned by WADA for athletes in competition. **Pharmacokinetics**: oral DHEA has poor bioavailability (~20%) due to extensive first-pass metabolism; sublingual and transdermal forms achieve higher serum levels. Half-life varies by form: oral ~30 minutes for parent compound but DHEA-S persists much longer (12–18 hours). Single morning dose typically produces 24-hour elevation.",
