    notes:
      "## Dosing by Use Case + Sex\n**Women — physiological replacement (most common use case):**\n- 5–10mg/day entry; assess for androgen conversion symptoms\n- 10–25mg/day maintenance; bracket with DHEA-S lab\n- >25mg/day rarely tolerated by women without androgen side effects\n- Topical compounded DHEA cream often preferred — better titration control, fewer side effects\n\n**Men — physiological replacement:**\n- 25mg/day entry\n- 25–50mg/day maintenance\n- 50–100mg/day high-end (some research protocols and aggressive longevity stacks)\n- Lab targeting: DHEA-S in young-adult reference range\n\n**Postmenopausal women — vaginal symptoms:** intravaginal DHEA (prasterone, FDA-approved as Intrarosa) 6.5mg/day intravaginally — bypasses systemic exposure while treating local atrophy. Prescription product but the active compound is identical to OTC DHEA.\n\n**Adrenal insufficiency context (Addison's, hypopituitarism):** women 25–50mg/day, men 25mg/day, in coordination with endocrinologist. The replacement use case in Addison's improves quality of life beyond cortisol replacement alone.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nWomen: start 10mg/day AM × 4 weeks, check DHEA-S labs at 6 weeks, adjust. Men: start 25mg/day AM × 4 weeks, check DHEA-S labs at 6 weeks, adjust. Track: energy, mood, libido, sleep quality, skin/hair changes.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nLayer with: Pregnenolone 25–50mg/day (upstream precursor — provides additional steroid pathway support), 7-Keto DHEA 100mg/day (non-androgenic metabolite for users wanting metabolic effects without androgen conversion), targeted nutritional support for adrenal function (vitamin C, B5/pantothenic acid, magnesium), comprehensive sleep optimization (sleep is the foundation for endogenous DHEA production). For comprehensive HRT context: layer with TRT (testosterone replacement), bioidentical estradiol/progesterone (women), thyroid optimization. Cardiovascular layer: omega-3, statin/Lp(a) management as indicated, cardio-metabolic markers.\n\nFor users running aggressive longevity stacks: DHEA fits alongside NMN/NR/TMG (NAD pathway), pterostilbene/fisetin/quercetin/apigenin/sulforaphane (senolytic/Nrf2/CD38), and rapamycin pulse-dosing.\n\n## DHEA vs 7-Keto DHEA — Decision Frame\nSee 7-Keto DHEA entry. The key distinction:\n- **DHEA** converts to androgens and estrogens via downstream metabolism — the 'precursor hormone' use case for HRT contexts\n- **7-Keto DHEA** does not convert to androgens or estrogens — useful for users wanting metabolic / immune / cognitive effects without sex hormone elevation; particularly relevant for users with hormone-sensitive cancer history, PCOS women, men wanting effects without aromatization\n\nMany users layer both (DHEA for hormonal precursor support + 7-Keto for additional metabolic effects without further androgen conversion).\n\n## Lab Monitoring\nBaseline + 6–8 weeks post-initiation + every 6–12 months thereafter:\n- **DHEA-S** (the stable circulating form; the primary monitoring marker)\n- **Total testosterone, free testosterone** (women: ensure not over-converting to androgens; men: assess if DHEA is contributing meaningfully)\n- **Estradiol** (sensitive assay — particularly for postmenopausal women, men with aromatization risk)\n- **Total PSA** (men over 40)\n- **Lipid panel, fasting glucose, HbA1c** (metabolic markers)\n- **Cortisol** (AM cortisol; assess HPA axis if relevant)\n\nTarget DHEA-S in young-adult reference range; do not exceed.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A for oral/sublingual. Topical compounded cream: applied to inner thigh, inner forearm, or other thin-skin areas; rotate sites; allow absorption before clothing contact. AM dosing matches endogenous circadian pattern.\n\n## Synergies\n**Pregnenolone:** upstream precursor; combinations are common in adrenal/longevity protocols. **7-Keto DHEA:** non-androgenic complement; layering provides hormonal precursor + metabolic effects without additional androgen conversion. **Ashwagandha:** HPA axis support, complementary mechanism. **Vitamin C / B5 / magnesium:** adrenal cofactor nutritional support.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nWolkowitz 1997 (Biological Psychiatry, n=22 midlife with major depression, 30-90mg/day × 6 weeks): improved mood, decreased depression scores. Villareal 2006 (Annals of Internal Medicine, n=70 elderly, 50mg/day × 12 months): improved BMD, bone turnover. Baulieu 2000 (PNAS, n=280 healthy elderly, 50mg/day × 12 months): improved skin, libido, bone density in subgroup analyses. Arlt 1999 (NEJM, n=24 women with adrenal insufficiency, 50mg/day × 4 months): improved well-being, mood, sexual function. Genazzani 2003 (n=24 postmenopausal women, 25mg/day × 12 months): improved mood, sexual function, bone metabolism markers.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nSubstantial RCT evidence base across multiple use contexts (adrenal insufficiency replacement, postmenopausal symptom management, midlife mood/well-being, bone density). Effect sizes modest in most studies; the strongest evidence is in adrenal insufficiency replacement and postmenopausal vaginal atrophy (Intrarosa). Long-term safety data accumulating but not as extensive as for some other supplements due to OTC status producing more variable real-world use.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid for adrenal insufficiency replacement, postmenopausal symptom management, modest effects on mood/well-being in midlife users with low baseline; effect sizes modest in healthy young adults with normal baseline DHEA-S. Anecdote: extensive use in HRT/integrative medicine contexts; subjective effects vary substantially based on baseline status; women particularly responsive when baseline is low. Decision frame: foundational adrenal/HRT support for users with documented low DHEA-S; layer with pregnenolone (upstream) and 7-Keto (non-androgenic complement); titrate to lab values rather than fixed dose; not a longevity-magic-bullet but reasonable component of comprehensive HRT/longevity protocols.",
