    mechanism:
      "Polyphenolic compound from the rhizome of **Curcuma longa** (turmeric), responsible for the spice's characteristic yellow-orange color and a substantial fraction of its biological activity. Curcumin is technically one of three closely related curcuminoids (curcumin, demethoxycurcumin, bisdemethoxycurcumin) collectively present in turmeric at ~3–5% by weight. Most research and supplementation focuses on curcumin specifically. **Mechanism — multi-pathway anti-inflammatory**: curcumin is mechanistically promiscuous in the best sense — it modulates dozens of inflammatory and cellular pathways. Major mechanisms: (1) **NF-κB pathway inhibition** — the master regulator of inflammatory cytokine production; curcumin inhibits NF-κB activation and translocation, reducing TNF-α, IL-1β, IL-6, IL-8 production; this is the primary clinically relevant anti-inflammatory mechanism. (2) **COX-2 and LOX inhibition** — anti-inflammatory at the prostaglandin/leukotriene level (similar enzymatic targets to NSAIDs but with broader pathway effects and milder direct enzyme inhibition). (3) **Nrf2 pathway activation** — antioxidant response element activation; upregulates endogenous antioxidant and detoxification enzyme expression (parallel mechanism to sulforaphane). (4) **Direct antioxidant activity** — curcumin's polyphenol structure makes it a moderate direct ROS scavenger. (5) **JAK-STAT pathway modulation** — affects multiple cytokine signaling cascades. (6) **PPAR-γ activation** — metabolic and anti-inflammatory effects. (7) **Modulation of growth factor pathways** (EGF, VEGF, others). (8) **Apoptosis induction in cancer cells** — via multiple pathways; substantial cancer-prevention research base. (9) **Amyloid-β interaction** — curcumin binds amyloid plaques in vitro and in animal models; potential Alzheimer's relevance. (10) **Microbiome effects** — modulation of gut bacterial populations. **Mechanism — bioavailability is the dominant practical issue**: standard curcumin has dramatically poor oral bioavailability — peak plasma concentrations are typically <1% of administered dose due to (a) poor water solubility, (b) extensive intestinal glucuronidation/sulfation, (c) rapid hepatic metabolism, (d) poor stability in gut alkaline environment. Without bioavailability enhancement, even 8g/day of standard curcumin produces minimal systemic exposure. The bioavailability problem has driven development of multiple enhanced formulations: Meriva (phytosome — Indena), Theracurmin (colloidal nanoparticle — Theravalues), BCM-95 (turmeric oils + curcuminoids), Longvida (solid lipid particle), liposomal curcumin (multiple brands), nano-curcumin, piperine-paired curcumin (the traditional turmeric-with-black-pepper approach — piperine inhibits glucuronidation, increasing curcumin bioavailability ~20-fold). Form selection matters substantially for clinical effect — the bioavailability differential between standard turmeric and well-formulated bioavailability-enhanced products can be 30–100×.",
