    mechanism:
      "Endogenous indoleamine hormone synthesized primarily in the pineal gland from serotonin via N-acetylation followed by O-methylation. Production follows a strong circadian rhythm — onset ~2 hours before habitual bedtime in dim light (DLMO — Dim Light Melatonin Onset, the gold-standard circadian phase marker), peak in middle of biological night, near-zero during daylight. Significant melatonin synthesis also occurs in extra-pineal sites including gut, retina, bone marrow, lymphocytes, and importantly **mitochondria** (where local concentrations may be 100–1000× pineal output). **Mechanism — circadian / sleep functions**: (1) **MT1 and MT2 receptor activation** — G-protein coupled receptors mediating sleep promotion, circadian phase shifting, and core body temperature reduction. MT2 receptors specifically mediate sleep latency reduction; MT1 mediates sleep maintenance and circadian phase effects. (2) **Phase-shifting properties** — exogenous melatonin in PM advances circadian phase; AM melatonin delays. The phase-response curve is well-characterized. (3) **Body temperature reduction** — melatonin lowers core body temperature, facilitating sleep onset. (4) **GABAergic potentiation** — modest indirect GABA enhancement contributing to sedative effect. **Mechanism — antioxidant / mitochondrial functions** (the higher-dose Reiter-school framing): (1) **Direct free radical scavenging** — melatonin is a potent direct antioxidant, with capacity to scavenge multiple reactive species (•OH, ONOO-, others); each melatonin molecule produces multiple antioxidant metabolites in cascade reactions, multiplying the effective antioxidant capacity. (2) **Mitochondrial protection** — local melatonin synthesis in mitochondria provides direct protection against oxidative damage at the site of major ROS production. (3) **Glutathione synthesis enhancement** — increases endogenous glutathione production. (4) **Anti-inflammatory effects** via NF-κB inhibition. (5) **Immune modulation** — enhanced T-cell function, particularly relevant in elderly with declining immune function. (6) **Anti-cancer activity** in animal models and emerging clinical evidence (particularly hormone-sensitive cancers). **Mechanism — neuroprotection**: substantial animal model and emerging human evidence for benefits in stroke, neurodegenerative disease, traumatic brain injury contexts. **The dose-paradigm divide — Pierpaoli vs Reiter framing**: melatonin supplementation has two distinct clinical paradigms with different dosing logic:\n\n**Pierpaoli school (low-dose physiological replacement):** 0.3–0.5mg/night targeting physiological replacement of declining endogenous production with age. The argument: pharmacological doses (3-10mg+) produce supraphysiological serum levels that may downregulate endogenous receptors and disrupt the natural pulsatile signal; physiological replacement preserves the natural signal pattern. Pierpaoli's research with this framing showed lifespan extension in mice.\n\n**Reiter school (high-dose therapeutic antioxidant):** 3–10mg+ (some research uses 100-300mg/day) targeting therapeutic antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects. The argument: melatonin's antioxidant and mitochondrial protection effects require pharmacological levels well above physiological; the receptor downregulation concern is overstated; high doses are exceptionally well-tolerated. Reiter's research established melatonin's antioxidant pharmacology.\n\nBoth frameworks have valid evidence bases; the choice depends on use case (sleep/circadian → low-dose; antioxidant/anti-inflammatory/cancer-adjunct → high-dose). Many users layer both (low PM dose for sleep + occasional high-dose for therapeutic windows).",
